The paper focuses on analyzing the performance of different massive MIMO and base station cooperation techniques in an indoor office scenario. This involves studying the impact of different precoding methods, channel state information, and antenna configurations on spectral efficiency, fairness, wall penetration loss, and inter-cell interference. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory), which deals with the mathematical foundations of communication systems. 

The paper also considers the impact of network infrastructure and coordination on the performance, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of distributed and centralized architectures, which could fall under the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. 

Furthermore, the paper involves analyzing the performance of massive MIMO systems, which could be classified under the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category that deals with multimedia signal processing and communication. Finally, the paper also discusses the impact of estimation errors on the performance, which could be relevant to the cs.AR (Augmented Reality and Virtual Reality) sub-category that deals with computer vision and image processing.
